    "question_type": "MCQ",
    "answer_type": "single_correct",
    "question_text": "If x and y are real numbers such that 2x + 3y > 12 and x − y < 2, then which of the following must be true?",
    "options": [
      {
        "id": "A",
        "text": "x > 4"
      },
      {
        "id": "B",
        "text": "y > 2"
      },
      {
        "id": "C",
        "text": "x + y > 4"
      },
      {
        "id": "D",
        "text": "x > y"
      }
    ],
    "correct_option": "C",
    "solution": {
      "final_answer": "x + y > 4",
      "explanation": {
        "concept": "Combine linear inequalities to eliminate variables and derive a bound on a new expression.",
        "step_by_step": [
          "Given: 2x + 3y > 12 ...(1) and x − y < 2 ...(2)",
          "From (2): x < y + 2",
          "Substitute into (1): 2(y + 2) + 3y > 12",
          "2y + 4 + 3y > 12 → 5y > 8 → y > 8/5",
          "From x < y + 2, take minimum possible x = y + 2 (boundary)",
          "Then x + y > (y + 2) + y = 2y + 2 > 2*(8/5) + 2 = 16/5 + 10/5 = 26/5 > 4"
        ],
        "why_correct": {
          "C": "Derived lower bound shows x + y must exceed 4."
        },
        "why_incorrect": {
          "A": "x need not exceed 4; depends on y.",
          "B": "y > 2 is not guaranteed; y > 8/5 is sufficient.",
          "D": "x may be less than y depending on values."
        }
      }
    },
